<div class="recipe-container">
    <h1>Malai Kofta Recipe</h1>

    <div class="recipe-description">
        <p><strong>Malai Kofta</strong> is a rich and creamy North Indian dish made of deep-fried vegetable dumplings (koftas) served in a rich, aromatic tomato-based gravy. It’s a popular dish in Indian cuisine, perfect for festive occasions and special meals.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ingredients">
        <h2>Ingredients</h2>
        <div class="ingredient-list">
            <div class="ingredient-item">For Koftas:
                <ul>
                    <li>1 cup Paneer (cottage cheese)</li>
                    <li>1/2 cup boiled mashed potatoes</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Cornflour</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Raisins</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Cashews</li>
                    <li>1/2 tsp Cardamom powder</li>
                    <li>Salt to taste</li>
                    <li>Oil for frying</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ingredient-item">For Gravy:
                <ul>
                    <li>2 medium Tomatoes, pureed</li>
                    <li>1 onion, finely chopped</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Ginger-garlic paste</li>
                    <li>1/2 cup Heavy cream</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Cashew paste</li>
                    <li>1 tsp Red chili powder</li>
                    <li>1/2 tsp Garam masala</li>
                    <li>1 tbsp Butter</li>
                    <li>Salt to taste</li>
                    <li>Coriander leaves for garnishing</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cooking-instructions">
        <h2>How to Cook</h2>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Make the Koftas:</strong> In a mixing bowl, combine paneer, mashed potatoes, cornflour, cardamom powder, raisins, cashews, and salt. Mix well to form a smooth dough.</li>
            <li>Divide the mixture into small balls (koftas) and deep fry them until golden brown. Set them aside on paper towels to remove excess oil.</li>
            <li><strong>Prepare the Gravy:</strong> Heat butter in a pan and sauté onions until golden brown. Add ginger-garlic paste and sauté for a minute.</li>
            <li>Add the pureed tomatoes, red chili powder, garam masala, and salt. Cook until the oil separates from the masala.</li>
            <li>Stir in cashew paste and cream. Cook for another 5 minutes to make a rich gravy.</li>
            <li><strong>Combine Koftas with Gravy:</strong> Gently place the koftas into the gravy and cook for 3-4 minutes. Garnish with fresh coriander leaves.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="tips">
        <h2>Tips & Variations</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>You can substitute paneer with mashed vegetables for a healthier alternative.</li>
            <li>If you prefer a spicy gravy, add extra green chilies or red chili powder.</li>
            <li>For a vegan version, replace cream with coconut milk and paneer with tofu.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="serve">
        <h2>Serving Suggestions</h2>
        <p>Serve Malai Kofta hot with naan, roti, or steamed basmati rice. It pairs wonderfully with a side of raita or a refreshing cucumber salad.</p>
    </div>
</div>
